{{zh-forms|alt=𨟍,𩫩,𩫏,𩫖}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
The original version on oracle bones shows a tall tower similar to [[京]] and [[高]] (< [[髙]]) which perhaps was part of the outer city walls in ancient Chinese cities. At the bottom, there was an enclosed space [[囗]] to represent city walls or a city in general and another tower.

Later, the tower at the bottom was stylized like the unrelated [[子]] and the enclosed space was drawn as the unrelated [[回]]. Hence, the whole character was written like {{zh-l|*𩫖}} and {{zh-l|*𩫏}}. Sometimes, the second variant had the bottom part contracted into [[十]].

Eventually, {{zh-l|*邑}} was added to form an {{Han compound|𩫖|t1=tall building|邑|t2=city|ls=ic|nocap=yes}}, hence [[𩫩]], sometimes simplified into [[𨟍]] – outer city walls with tall towers.

From {{w|clerical script}}, the {{zh-l|*𩫖}} became written as the unrelated {{zh-l|*享}} through the process of ''{{w|libian}}''; the two characters are unrelated.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s/r-kawk ~ s/r-kwak||outer covering; skin, bark, rind}} (STEDT, {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).
; “to be none of someone's own business”
: Contraction of {{zh-m|[[關]][[我]]／[[关]][[我]]|tr=guān wǒ}}, short for {{m|zh|關……屁事|關我屁事|tr=guān wǒ pìshì}}.

